items.title: HTTP/2 Protocol: Transfer-Encoding Header Accepted

details.Technical Details: [[markup]]The target system accepts a **Transfer-Encoding: Chunked** header and body which is not permitted in the HTTP/2 spec. This can allow HTTP request smuggling in some configurations.

items.description:
[[markup]]The remote server accepted a malformed HTTP/2 message. In come cases this tolerance to malformed requests
can introduce security flaws.

This finding is reported to aid in the research of HTTP/2 and H2 to H1 translation vulnerabilities and may not
be readily exploitable.
items.solution:
[[markup]]Ensure that the system accepting HTTP/2 connections is kept up-to-date. Several vulnerabilities and attack
techniques were published in August and September 2021 that leveraged discrepancies in processing HTTP/2
requests, therefore updates may follow to harden the affected device.

This finding is reported as part of the HTTP/2 assessment process and may not constitute a specific
vulnerability.

[[markup]]The remote server accepted a malformed HTTP/2 message. In come cases this tolerance to malformed requests
can introduce security flaws.

items.title: HTTP/2 Protocol: Transfer-Encoding Header Accepted

details.Technical Details: [[markup]]The target system accepts a **Transfer-Encoding: Chunked** header and body which is not permitted in the HTTP/2 spec. This can allow HTTP request smuggling in some configurations.

items.description:
[[markup]]The remote server accepted a malformed HTTP/2 message. In come cases this tolerance to malformed requests
can introduce security flaws.

This finding is reported to aid in the research of HTTP/2 and H2 to H1 translation vulnerabilities and may not
be readily exploitable.
items.solution:
[[markup]]Ensure that the system accepting HTTP/2 connections is kept up-to-date. Several vulnerabilities and attack
techniques were published in August and September 2021 that leveraged discrepancies in processing HTTP/2
requests, therefore updates may follow to harden the affected device.

This finding is reported as part of the HTTP/2 assessment process and may not constitute a specific
vulnerability.
